trans-unit.source: Specifies the relative priority of items stored in the <xref href="System.Web.Caching.Cache"></xref> object.
When the Web server hosting an ASP.NET application runs low on memory, the <xref:System.Web.Caching.Cache> object selectively purges items to free system memory.
When an item is added to the cache, you can assign it a relative priority compared to the other items stored in the cache.

Items to which you assign higher priority values are less likely to be deleted from the cache when the server is processing a large number of requests, whereas items to which you assign lower priority values are more likely to be deleted.
Items can always be removed from the cache programmatically, regardless of their cache priority.
Cache items with this priority level are less likely to be deleted as the server frees system memory than those assigned a <xref href="System.Web.Caching.CacheItemPriority.Normal"></xref> priority.

Cache items with this priority level are more likely to be deleted from the cache as the server frees system memory than items assigned a <xref href="System.Web.Caching.CacheItemPriority.Normal"></xref> priority.
The default value for a cached item's priority is <xref href="System.Web.Caching.CacheItemPriority.Normal"></xref>.
Cache items with this priority level are the least likely to be deleted from the cache as the server frees system memory.
Cache items with this priority level are the most likely to be deleted from the cache as the server frees system memory.

Cache items with this priority level are likely to be deleted from the cache as the server frees system memory only after those items with <xref href="System.Web.Caching.CacheItemPriority.Low"></xref> or <xref href="System.Web.Caching.CacheItemPriority.BelowNormal"></xref> priority.
The cache items with this priority level will not be automatically deleted from the cache as the server frees system memory.
However, items with this priority level are removed along with other items according to the item's absolute or sliding expiration time.
